"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[103],{7103:e=>{e.exports=JSON.parse('{"id":0,"title":"Introduction","description":"","content":{"html":"<p><em><strong>Notes:</strong></em></p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><em>This book is currently being written, only the introduction and the first two chapters are available at the moment (approximately 120 pages).</em></li>\\n</ul>\\n<p><em><strong>Notes on the English translation (I am writing this book in French):</strong></em></p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><em>I will use the word \\"sense\\" as a literal translation of the French \\"sens\\", with the dual meaning of \\"meaning\\" and \\"direction\\". So, the \\"sense of History\\" means something like: the \\"meaning of the dynamics of History\\". It means that the History has a meaning and also a direction—it\'s going somewhere. The underlying idea is that something that\'s going nowhere doesn\'t have a sense. This meaning of the word \\"sense\\" is found in the expression \\"the sense of a vector\\" in math in english.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Links to external content sometimes point to videos and websites in French. I\'ll be replacing them with English links over the next few months (perhaps with your help—you can recommend English-language content to me by clicking the icon in the top right corner).</em></li>\\n</ul>\\n<h2 id=\\"29f0b424-af42-43ca-b4fc-b258e0d31bf4\\">Welcome to the Future</h2>\\n<p>You’ve probably already sensed it, but let me say it out loud: <strong>we’ve just stepped into the Future.</strong> After Prehistory, Antiquity, the Middle Ages, the Renaissance, the Modern Era, and then the Contemporary Era, we’ve just entered a new era in human history: the Future. AI, robots, human genome sequencing for €200, ultra-high-speed internet everywhere on Earth—even in the middle of the desert—and the environmental consequences of it all: we’re here. Bienvenue!</p>\\n<p>But today, the Future is beyond us. Nothing seems ready to welcome it. And, faced with the impact of AI, many wonder whether human beings still have a role to play in the Future. I assert that they do—and more than that, I assert that human beings are the sole driving force behind the history of the universe today. And that is the vision I will present in this book.</p>\\n<p>This vision is based on three key convictions:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>The universe and human history have a sense, and this sense leads us toward ever greater power, wealth, freedom, justice, science, technology, art, beauty, and so on</li>\\n<li>The sense of the universe requires human beings to be realized; therefore, each of us has a role to play and a responsibility in our own lives, the future of society, and the universe</li>\\n<li>The sense of the universe can only be realized through cooperation; therefore, each of us must strive to demonstrate high standards, kindness, and solidarity with their fellow human beings</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>In other words, the aim of this book is to present the natural dynamics of the universe and how this \\"sense of History\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-1\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-1\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">1</a></sup> manifests itself in all areas: from biology to politics, including science, technology, justice, culture, art, love, sex, and gastronomy. But it will also explores what the \\"place of Man\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-2\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-2\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">2</a></sup> is within this History—that is, the role we have to play in it, both individually and collectively.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"8a5b7fbd-0db0-4f61-a3a8-29f24d713104\\">So, Why this Book?</h2>\\n<p>It\'s simple. All my life, I\'ve heard nothing but pessimistic, stupid, or suicidal speech. I\'ve never heard a single positive and serious vision of the future. <strong>For at least 30 years, politicians and intellectuals seem to have completely given up in the face of the modern world\'s complexity.</strong> The modern world does indeed seem too complex for us to truly find solutions to ecological, economic, and social problems. Yet our future depends on these solutions. If no one finds a solution, humanity could very well destroy itself in another world war, or our societies could collapse into widespread chaos.</p>\\n<p>Faced with this somewhat alarming situation, I initially felt helpless. But as I delved into human history, I realized that our ancestors had already faced many other challenges. The <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Death\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Black Death</a>, for example. A plague that appeared out of nowhere in 1346, wiping out 50% of Europe\'s population and killing more than 75 million people worldwide. And all that in just seven years. Yet, despite that tragedy, I am writing these lines and you are reading them today.</p>\\n<p>Taking a step back, <strong>I\'ve come to a realization: <em>we are living in the idealistic dream of our ancestors.</em></strong> The world in which we grew up and live today would seem to them like some kind of fantastical paradise. Could they have imagined a world:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Almost completely free of famine and diseases such as the plague, smallpox, polio, leprosy, tuberculosis, etc.</li>\\n<li>Where 86% of the world\'s population can read and write</li>\\n<li>Where 70% of the world\'s population has access to the internet and can communicate instantly across the globe</li>\\n<li>And with running water, electricity, 40% of the population pursuing higher education, free hospitals, etc., in the most advanced countries</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Yes, they had imagined this world. For the world we live in today is precisely the one they built. Through the hard work of generations, their dream became a reality. Each generation faced the challenges of its time and overcame them.</p>\\n<p>Now, the modern world is far more complex than that of our ancestors. There is no guarantee that the challenges of the 21st century can be overcome like those of the past. However, taking this step back made me wonder: what if it were possible? What if it were possible to find solutions to all ecological, economic, and social problems?</p>\\n<p>For the first time, I no longer assumed we were doomed. For the first time, I no longer felt completely powerless. <strong>I then set out in search of an answer: is it possible to overcome all the problems of our time? And, if so, how?</strong></p>\\n<p>First of all, to find out if these problems could be solved, I had to start by understanding them. I had always heard about environmental, economic, and social issues, but I didn\'t really know exactly what they entailed. So I started doing research and reading voraciously to try to understand as many topics as possible. This led me to take an interest in everything: <em>from biology to politics, including science, technology, justice, culture, art, love, sex, and gastronomy</em>.</p>\\n<p>At the same time, I told myself that I couldn\'t be the only one on this quest. And, above all, I couldn\'t be the first. So I sought to get involved in existing projects. That meant I first had to know what was out there. So I went to meet with a multitude of organizations, associations, and political parties.</p>\\n<p>At first, I was drawn in by certain arguments and personalities. But as I did my own research, I began to see their limitations. The more I explored the world, the more I realized that those who speak with conviction in the media and political parties don\'t understand much beyond their very narrow subject matter.</p>\\n<p>The outcome of this journey was somewhat paradoxical:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>On the one hand, I realized that almost no one has a comprehensive and coherent view of the world today, which was a bit depressing</li>\\n<li>But, on the other hand, it meant one thing: if all those who claim we\'re doomed don\'t understand what they\'re talking about, then maybe the 1% of optimists are right, which was very encouraging</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p><strong>I even came up with an idea: <em>pessimism is an admission of failure</em>.</strong> Instead of admitting they\'ve failed to find solutions, intellectuals claim we\'re doomed (or that we need a revolution to change everything, without specifying what exactly).</p>\\n<p>So, my journey has led me to a conviction: <strong>the prevailing sense of fatalism does not mean that ecological, economic, and social problems are impossible to solve, but rather that no one has succeeded yet.</strong> And that changes everything. In science, failing to solve a problem for years, or even decades, before finally succeeding is the norm. And scientists can fail 100 times to solve a problem without ever claiming that it is impossible to solve. In fact, very often, the more difficult a problem is, the more exciting it is. And that is exactly how I felt when I began to take an interest in the future of humanity: are ecological, economic, and social problems very difficult to solve? All the better! If they were easy, they would be much less interesting.</p>\\n<p>Along the way, without even realizing it, I became passionate about these topics. <strong>Developing a comprehensive and coherent vision of the future became something of an obsession for me.</strong> And the years began to pass. But I couldn\'t seem to find a clear guiding principle. I kept accumulating more and more knowledge and ideas, but my worldview still lacked a backbone.</p>\\n<p>Then, a year ago, everything changed. While browsing online, I stumbled upon an image from the work of astrophysicist Eric Chaisson.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/master_chaisson_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;margin:auto;width:100%;height:auto;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1.5rem;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>energy dissipated as a function of age of appearance, on a <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6fMLp5WOx08\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">logarithmic scale</a> (reproduction of an image from the book Cosmic Evolution by <a href=\\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/241317796_Cosmic_Evolution_-_State_of_the_Science_in_Cosmos_and_Culture_S_Dick_and_M_Lupisella_eds_NASA_Press_SP-4802_pp_3-23_Washington_2009\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Eric Chaisson</a> and reworked by <a href=\\"https://www.francois-roddier.fr/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Fran\xe7ois Roddier</a> in his book <a href=\\"https://www.francois-roddier.fr/?p=262\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Thermodynamics of Evolution</a>).</em></p>\\n<p>At first glance, I didn\'t grasp all the details of this graph. But <strong>I quickly understood its general meaning: the universe has a sense</strong>, and that sense leads us toward increasingly complex systems. More specifically, toward systems that are increasingly powerful per unit of mass (which corresponds to the weight-to-power ratio of cars). For the same mass, a human being is a more powerful system than the sun. 1 m\xb3 of the sun weighs about 1,500 kg and produces 0.3 W. Meanwhile, a human being weighs about 70 kg and produces between 100 and 500 W depending on the intensity of their physical activity. In other words, a human being is about 10,000 times more powerful per kg than the sun, and this is what the image above represents (Chapter 3 will be entirely devoted to explaining this image and debunking entropy).</p>\\n<p><strong>Discovering this image felt like a revelation to me.</strong> It was as if I had always known it and had suddenly become aware of it. All of a sudden, all my observations and analyses of the world, society, and human life finally found a broader sense of the universe in which to be understood. Concretely, on a human scale, this natural dynamic of the universe leads us toward ever greater wealth, freedom, justice, science, technology, art, beauty, and so on. In short, power is wealth (we will explore this idea in more detail in Chapter 4 on the purpose of life).</p>\\n<p><strong>But this image goes further, for it also speaks to the \\"place of Man\\"</strong> in the universe. Today, the human being is the most powerful system we know of in the universe. By \\"powerful\\", we must also understand \\"intelligent\\". And it is this \\"intelligence\\" that is today the only actor capable of continuing the universe\'s 13.8 billion years of evolution. That is, of creating systems even more powerful than human beings : human societies.</p>\\n<p>Concretely, the transition from hunter-gatherer societies to industrial societies is a natural extension of the history of the universe. An industrial society is a more powerful system per kilogram than a hunter-gatherer society. Just as a human being is more powerful per kilogram than the sun. The difference here is that the evolution from a star like the sun to a human being is the result of nuclear and chemical reactions, followed by natural selection. Whereas the evolution from a hunter-gatherer society to an industrial society is the result of human intelligence and will.</p>\\n<p>Here is an image to support this idea (this image will also be discussed in detail in Chapter 3):</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/macro_micro_evoluion_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;margin:auto;width:100%;height:auto;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1.5rem;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>the history of the universe is an alternation between micro and macro evolution (reproduction of an image from the book The Self-organizing Universe by Eric Jantsh and reworked by Fran\xe7ois Roddier in his book <a href=\\"https://www.francois-roddier.fr/?p=706\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Thermodynamics of Evolution</a>)</em>.</p>\\n<p>In other words, it is indeed human beings who are today the only agents capable of developing ever more powerful systems to drive the evolution of the universe. This must be reflected, in particular, in our use of intelligence and willpower to solve ecological, economic, and social problems.</p>\\n<p><strong>This, then, is the very purpose of this book: <em>the sense of History and the place of Man</em>.</strong></p>\\n<p>For now, this introduction probably seems a bit abstract to you, or even completely mystical. So let\'s now look at a concrete illustration of the sense of History.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"5acd0925-a9ad-4608-a586-f3571dbcb1b9\\">Have Communists Changed the Course of History?</h2>\\n<p>On November 7, 1917, the communist revolutionaries seized power in Russia. This marked the birth of the USSR: the \\"Union of Soviet Socialist Republics.\\" A few years later, the communist government launched a policy of intensive industrialization. This policy led to a massive migration of peasants to the cities to work in factories. As a result, by 1950 in Russia, 40% of the population lived in cities, compared to just 15% in 1917. And the proportion of workers and employees had risen from about 20% in 1917 to 50% in 1950. As a result, in 33 years, daily life had completely changed for a large portion of Russians.</p>\\n<p>Reflecting on these events, I asked myself a question: what would have happened if the 1917 revolution had failed? How would Russia have evolved? We can answer these questions by observing how other countries around the world have evolved over the past 100 years. Virtually all countries have industrialized, adopted socialist measures, and seen their populations concentrate in cities.</p>\\n<p>Concretely, today:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Every country in the world has internet access and uses information technology (even if not everyone in those countries has access to it).</li>\\n<li>Every country in the world has become urbanized and continues to do so today.</li>\\n<li>And as for socialist measures, even the United States established a <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_programs_in_the_United_States\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">social safety net</a> as early as the 1930s, including assistance for the unemployed, the elderly, people with disabilities, and certain low-income families. In other words, all countries that had sufficient wealth to redistribute have redistributed a portion of that wealth, as demanded by socialist movements.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Based on these observations, the answer for Russia seemed strangely obvious to me: without the 1917 revolution, the Russian monarchy would also have industrialized Russia, adopted socialist measures, and seen populations concentrate in the cities. Admittedly, this transformation might have taken place more slowly and under very different conditions, but it would have happened nonetheless, just as it did in every other country in the world.</p>\\n<p>In other words, behind revolutions and, more broadly, wars and chaos, there does indeed seem to be a sense, a direction toward which we are inevitably heading. But what is that sense? What is the sense of human history?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"8eb8905a-c000-4785-bccb-7090b5ce6249\\">The Sense of Human History</h2>\\n<img src=\\"/media/information_cerveau_solution_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;margin:auto;width:100%;height:auto;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1.5rem;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>Let\'s look at a summary of the main idea of this book: all progress in human history has come from the human mind. The sense of human history, which leads us toward ever greater wealth, freedom, justice, science, technology, art, beauty, and so on, always rests on the exercise of the human mind. That is to say, development:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Science, technology, and technique</li>\\n<li>Spirituality, that is, the mental framework that enables individuals to use their minds and bodies ever more effectively (which is achieved primarily through education, starting with the acquisition of language)</li>\\n<li>And just social organizations<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-3\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-3\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">3</a></sup> that enable people to cooperate effectively (Chapter 7 will be devoted to the concept of justice)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Concretely, who has done the most to raise the standard of living for the working class, advance women\'s liberation, and make education accessible? Scientists, engineers, and entrepreneurs (public or private) and, more broadly, all those who have created through their minds. Of course, this includes all those who have developed spirituality and social organizations, but there is no real word to describe them today other than the catch-all term \\"entrepreneur\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-4\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-4\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">4</a></sup>. Words like intellectual, journalist, spiritual leader, theologian, politician, reformer, administrator, technocrat, activist, etc., encompass too many things that have nothing to do with progress to be used today.</p>\\n<p>When I arrived at this view of human history, it seemed almost too simple to be true. And I asked myself: if it\'s that simple, why does hardly anyone talk about it? Why is most media discourse so depressing? The entire history of humanity is a story of progress despite the difficulties—why not be optimistic? More broadly, are there legitimate reasons to question the \\"myth of progress\\"? We can answer this question with a graph: the \\"elephant curve\\".</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"03fa2513-76df-4e6e-b004-3f985ba916a8\\">Why the West No Longer Believes in Progress</h2>\\n<img src=\\"/media/courbe_elephant_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;margin:auto;width:100%;height:auto;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1.5rem;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>this graph shows the growth rate of average real<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-5\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-5\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">5</a></sup> income (vertical axis) for each income bracket of the global population, from the poorest on the left to the richest on the right (horizontal axis), over two periods: from 1988 to 2008 (black) and from 2008 to 2018 (gray). The shape of the curve for the first period earned it the nickname “elephant curve” (reproduction of an image from Branko Milanovic’s article <a href=\\"https://osf.io/preprints/socarxiv/yg2h9_v1\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">The Three Eras of Global Inequality</a>; I added the circle to indicate the Western middle classes).</em></p>\\n<p>In summary:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Emerging economies (primarily China) have grown immensely wealthy thanks to globalization and industrialization over both periods.</li>\\n<li>The global top 1% benefited enormously from globalization between 1988 and 2008, but their incomes have remained relatively stagnant since the 2008 financial crisis (but, although it does not appear in this study, the incomes of the top 0.001% <a href=\\"https://ses.ens-lyon.fr/fichiers/Articles/worldinequalityreport2022-full-report.pdf\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">skyrocketed over both periods</a>).</li>\\n<li>The Western middle classes (80th to 90th percentile) have completely stagnated over both periods (this is less visible in the graph for the second period, as they are averaged with the Asian middle classes, which continued to grow after reaching their level).</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Thus, this graph clearly shows that the majority of humanity has benefited from scientific and technological progress over the past 40 years, except for the Western middle classes (appearing around the 80th to 90th percentile on the horizontal axis). In other words, those who question the \\"myth of progress\\" are simply those who have not benefited from it. The rest of the world—that is, 90% of humanity—believes more than ever in progress, science, and technology. Concretely, the Islamic Republic of Iran trains more engineers per year than France does today (with a population of 87 million compared to France\'s 69 million).</p>\\n<p>The question of whether humanity will continue to progress is therefore not even up for debate. The same goes for space exploration. China will colonize space. There should therefore be a permanent human base on the Moon by the end of the century. And that will happen even if there are one or more world wars in the meantime.</p>\\n<p>I\'m confident in saying this because understanding the \\"sense of History\\" truly allows us to predict the future in the medium and long term. To illustrate this, let\'s look at an example of a prediction that came true.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"b2b12c9c-9aac-4712-8f2f-4145c46509f1\\">How the Emergence of \\"Intelligent\\" AI Was Predicted in 2013</h2>\\n<p>Imagine it\'s 2013, and you want to estimate the date when AI will become as \\"intelligent\\" as a human being. To do that, you need two things:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>An estimate of the human brain\'s computing power</li>\\n<li>And the pace of technological progress, which is increasing the computing power of computers</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Logically, when computers reach the same computational power as the human brain, the existence of an AI as \\"intelligent\\" as a human being will become possible and is therefore likely to emerge. Now, is there a law that predicts the speed of technological progress? Yes, it is Moore\'s Law.</p>\\n<a href=\\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/00/Moore%27s_Law_Transistor_Count_1970-2020.png\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">  \\n<img src=\\"/media/loi_moore.png\\" style=\\"display:block;margin:auto;width:100%;height:auto;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1.5rem;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n</a>\\n<p>In 1965, Gordon E. Moore (one of the founders of the microprocessor company Intel, which powers about 70% of computers today) observed that the number of <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transistor\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">transistors</a> on a microprocessor chip had been doubling every year at constant cost since 1959 (the year they were invented). His observation, after a few adjustments, became \\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moore%27s_law\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Moore\'s Law</a>\\": an empirical law predicting that the number of transistors on a microprocessor chip would double every two years. And this law, after a few more adjustments, has held true for 50 years (even though it seems to be reaching its limits in recent years due to the physical limits of miniaturization<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-6\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-6\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">6</a></sup>).</p>\\n<p>From there, you have:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>An extrapolation of Moore\'s Law proposed by Intel scientists, who predict that computing power will double every 18 months</li>\\n<li>And an estimate of the human brain\'s computing power made by neuroscientists</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>After a calculation that a 12-year-old could do (multiplying by 2), you get a date: 2025.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/progres_ia_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;margin:auto;width:100%;height:auto;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1.5rem;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>Yes, in 2013, in <a href=\\"https://www.motherjones.com/media/2013/05/robots-artificial-intelligence-jobs-automation/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">this article</a>, Kevin Drum (journalist) predicted the date of AI\'s emergence by extrapolating Moore\'s Law. In reality, ChatGPT was released in late 2022, but it wasn\'t until May 2024 (the release of version 4o) that it became truly good. His prediction therefore turned out to be surprisingly accurate<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-7\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-7\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">7</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>I wanted to share this example with you because it made a deep impression on me. By spending just five minutes thinking through information easily found online, it was literally possible to predict the future. In other words, behind all the sterile political debates and pessimistic speech, the course of History continues. And this simple fact allows us to predict the broad outlines of the future.</p>\\n<p>However, this progress is neither \\"natural\\" nor easy. Moore\'s Law did not come about by magic or because it was meant to be. Advances in computing and the creation of ChatGPT are the result of a colossal effort. To reach this point, billions of people had to use their intelligence and work together. More broadly, the comfort and wealth we enjoy today are not the result of chance, but rather the result of the work of the 7,000 generations of <em>Homo sapiens</em> who came before us. Once again, we live in the world that our ancestors built with the strength of their minds and their hands.</p>\\n<p>Thus, as mentioned earlier, History has a sense, but that sense requires human beings to be realized today. The future of the universe and our future—both individual and collective—rest on human intelligence and will. And AIs are simply powerful tools to help us. Which brings us to the final point:</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"cad8d200-9f15-4a28-8415-278676d7fea3\\">Build the Future</h2>\\n<p>What is humanity’s place in the Future? How can we live happily in the Future? How should the societies of the Future be organized? How to Build the Cities of the Future? These questions are no longer the stuff of science fiction, because, as stated in the introduction, we have just entered the Future. These, then, are the big questions we must answer today in order to build the Future.</p>\\n<p>The central aim of this book is to answer these questions by presenting a comprehensive vision of human history and its future—a vision in which human beings, through their intellect and will, are the driving force of history.</p>\\n<p>I will publish the chapters of this book as I write them. For now, only the first two are available. Each subsequent chapter should take me about two months to complete. Here are the tentative titles:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Chapter 1: Problem, Consciousness, Solution</li>\\n<li>Chapter 2: The Content of Consciousness and the World of Ideas</li>\\n<li>Chapter 3: The Will to Power of the Universe</li>\\n<li>Chapter 4: Origin, History, and Purpose of Life</li>\\n<li>Chapter 5: The Conquest of his Freedom</li>\\n<li>Chapter 6: Love and the Immortality of the Soul</li>\\n<li>Chapter 7: The Structure of Society and the Sense of Justice</li>\\n<li>Chapter 8: The Sense of Art and of Its History</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>If I\'m optimistic, I should have the whole thing finished within a year, by July 2027.</p>","toc":[{"id":"1c76bddf-437c-4304-a51b-b0ec3cc4603a","text":"","level":1,"children":[{"id":"29f0b424-af42-43ca-b4fc-b258e0d31bf4","text":"Welcome to the Future","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"8a5b7fbd-0db0-4f61-a3a8-29f24d713104","text":"So, Why this Book?","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"5acd0925-a9ad-4608-a586-f3571dbcb1b9","text":"Have Communists Changed the Course of History?","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"8eb8905a-c000-4785-bccb-7090b5ce6249","text":"The Sense of Human History","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"03fa2513-76df-4e6e-b004-3f985ba916a8","text":"Why the West No Longer Believes in Progress","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"b2b12c9c-9aac-4712-8f2f-4145c46509f1","text":"How the Emergence of \\"Intelligent\\" AI Was Predicted in 2013","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"cad8d200-9f15-4a28-8415-278676d7fea3","text":"Build the Future","level":2,"children":[]}]}],"footnotes":"<hr>\\n<section data-footnotes=\\"\\" class=\\"footnotes\\"><h2 class=\\"sr-only\\" id=\\"\\">Footnotes</h2>\\n<ol>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-1\\">\\n<p>\\"History\\" with a capital \\"H\\" can generally refer to two things: either the entirety of human history, or the academic discipline that studies that history. In this book, I will use it to refer to the entire history of the world from the origin of the universe to the present day. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-1\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 1\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-2\\">\\n<p>I will use the word \\"Man\\" with a capital \\"M\\" as a synonym for human. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-2\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 2\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-3\\">\\n<p>In terms of social organization, the current economic, social, and political system is 100 times more complex than medieval feudalism. Concretely, the French state, with its 15 ministries and constellation of subdivisions, is far more complex than the royal administration of the 11th century. Quite simply because the king did not have to manage 48,950 elementary schools, 6,950 middle schools, 3,750 high schools, 3,500 universities, 18 nuclear power plants, 27,000 km of railways, 875,000 km of drinking water pipelines, and an infinite number of other structures and organizations. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-3\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 3\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-4\\">\\n<p>I invite linguists to come up with some. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-4\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 4\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-5\\">\\n<p>\\"Real\\" is the opposite of \\"nominal.\\" \\"Real\\" income is income adjusted for inflation. For example, if your salary increased by 10% this year, but inflation was also 10%, your \\"nominal\\" income increased by 10%, but your “real” income remained the same. This is because, if everything costs 10% more due to inflation, earning 10% more only allows you to maintain the same purchasing power as before, not to increase it. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-5\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 5\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-6\\">\\n<p>The smallest transistors currently measure 2 nanometers (or about 10 silicon atoms). However, at this scale, current leakage and unpredictable quantum effects begin to appear. And, in any case, we do not know how to manufacture transistors smaller than an atom (about 0.1 or 0.2 nm), if that is even possible. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-6\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 6\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-7\\">\\n<p>The more cautious among us would argue that having the same computational power as the human brain is not enough to match human intelligence. That is true. However, that computational power was nonetheless a prerequisite for even hoping to match human intelligence. And now, that prerequisite has been met. The difference between AI and the human brain therefore no longer lies \\"solely\\" in their structure. That said, based on my current understanding of the human brain and AI, I believe that <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_general_intelligence\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">AGI</a> is unattainable without several technological revolutions. Furthermore, I believe that recent developments in AI obscure the enormous amount of content creation work carried out by humans over the past 15 years, while remaining entirely dependent on them. In short, ChatGPT without Wikipedia and YouTube would be worthless. The same goes for <a href=\\"https://www.midjourney.com/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Midjourney</a> without DeviantArt, Pinterest and potentially platforms for photographers like Shutterstock. And <a href=\\"https://cursor.com/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Cursor</a> (or any AI model for code, more specifically) without GitHub and frameworks like Next.js. In other words, most AI systems simply reproduce what has been published online over the past 15 years. What strikes us as incredible is above all the discovery of content created over the past 15 years and the ease with which we can manipulate it using this new software. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-7\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 7\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n</ol>\\n</section>","frontmatter":{}}}')}}]);